description.value: A flask in the form of Bes seated on a cylindrical stand with top and bottom mouldings. He is naked and sits with the soles of his feet together, and with his hands resting on his thighs. The mouth of the flask is lost, together with his plumes and probably a handle or handles. A voluted tendril survives at the left side of his forehead. The rear is plain, except for his buttocks. There is a base-ring, within which is an incuse broken-barred alpha, probably formed in the mould. Three-piece mould. Reduced fabric: grey Nile silt with some mica; coated with a black slip: Memphis Black Ware.

description.value: Head of a female limestone figure; painted. The surface is worn, especially around the tips of nose and chin, mouth and left ear. Traces of red paint on the lips, black in the fold between veil and neck. Longish, slender face with embossed eyes, fairly sturdy nose, a very small mouth with thin lips and a pointy chin. Covering the hair is a closely fitted veil which partially covers the ears. The thickened earlobes hint at jewelled ears. On the left shoulder traces of a necklace are visible. The back is flat but not entirely smoothed.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Seilenos with a panther.  Seilenos standing on a ground-line above a low plinth, naked and with his legs apart. He is bearded and balding, wearing a tightly woven wreath crossed by a horizontal fillet. He has anklets or possibly boots. A hole for the insertion of a separately made large phallus remains at the appropriate place. He holds a kantharos in his lowered left hand, and supports a panther with his right hand as it reaches across him to drink from the cup. At his left side a vine with a bunch of grapes grows up. The back is plain, with a suspension-lug placed behind the satyr’s neck.  Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt, with the remains of a white dressing, mainly on the front. Traces of pink paint remain on the flesh of Seilenos.
